1) Finding the Optimal Number of Clusters Using a Dendrogram¶

Using the Dendrogram to Determine the Optimal Number of Clusters. In the Iris dataset, the optimal number of clusters is determined to be 3 clusters, corresponding to the three flower types: Iris-setosa, Iris-versicolor, and Iris-virginica.

In [7]:
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
dendrogram = sch.dendrogram(sch.linkage(X_iris, method='ward'))
plt.title('Dendrogram for Iris Dataset')
plt.xlabel('Samples')
plt.ylabel('Euclidean distances')
plt.show()

3) Visualizing the clusters:¶

In [10]:
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.scatter(X_iris[y_hc_iris == 0, 0], X_iris[y_hc_iris == 0, 1], s=50, label='Cluster 1')
plt.scatter(X_iris[y_hc_iris == 1, 0], X_iris[y_hc_iris == 1, 1], s=50, label='Cluster 2')
plt.scatter(X_iris[y_hc_iris == 2, 0], X_iris[y_hc_iris == 2, 1], s=50, label='Cluster 3')

plt.title('Clusters of Iris Dataset')
plt.xlabel('Sepal Length (cm)')
plt.ylabel('Sepal Width (cm)')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [11]:
feature_pairs = [
    (0, 1),  # Sepal Length vs Sepal Width
    (0, 2),  # Sepal Length vs Petal Length
    (0, 3),  # Sepal Length vs Petal Width
    (1, 2),  # Sepal Width vs Petal Length
    (1, 3),  # Sepal Width vs Petal Width
    (2, 3)   # Petal Length vs Petal Width
]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
for idx, (i, j) in enumerate(feature_pairs, 1):
    plt.subplot(2, 3, idx)
    plt.scatter(X_iris[y_hc_iris == 0, i], X_iris[y_hc_iris == 0, j], s=50, label='Cluster 1')
    plt.scatter(X_iris[y_hc_iris == 1, i], X_iris[y_hc_iris == 1, j], s=50, label='Cluster 2')
    plt.scatter(X_iris[y_hc_iris == 2, i], X_iris[y_hc_iris == 2, j], s=50, label='Cluster 3')
    plt.xlabel(dataset.columns[i + 1])
    plt.ylabel(dataset.columns[j + 1])
    plt.legend()

plt.suptitle('Hierarchical Clustering on Different Feature Pairs of the Iris Dataset')
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])
plt.show()
